%N A394102 Shortest sides x for integer-sided triangles (x <= y <= z) with an integer internal angle bisector l splitting the triangle into two integer-sided triangles; include only tuples (x, y, z; l) with gcd(x, y, z, l) = 1; ordered by z, then y, then x.
%C A394102 The longest and middle sides are listed as A394100 and A394101, respectively. The corresponding l-values are in A393193.
%H A394102 Felix Huber, <a href="/A394102/b394102.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%e A394102 5 is a term because in the triangle (x, y, z) = (5, 5, 6) the internal bisector l_z = 4 splits z = 6 into 3 and 3, yielding two congruent triangles (3, 4, 5), and gcd(5, 5, 6, 4) = 1.
%e A394102 12 is a term because in the triangle (x, y, z) = (12, 15, 18) the internal bisector l_y = 10 splits y = 15 into 6 and 9, yielding triangles (6, 10, 12) and (9, 10, 18), and gcd(12, 15, 18, 10) = 1.
%p A394102 # See Huber link in A394100.
